See https://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=98294#c9.

Here is how to create Composite.wav from the indidividual responses:

AUDIO_DIR="WebKit/Source/platform/audio/resources"
sox $( \
  for azimuth in {0..23}; do \
    for elevation in 0 15 30 45 60 75 90 315 330 345; do \
      printf "$AUDIO_DIR/IRC_Composite_C_R0195_T%03d_P%03d.wav\n" "$(expr $azimuth \* 15)" "$elevation"; \
    done; \
  done;) \
Composite.wav

To create the FLAC-encoded version:

ffmpeg -i Composite.wav -c:a flac -compression_level 12 \
    -exact_rice_parameters 1 -lpc_type cholesky -lpc_passes 20 \
    -map_metadata -1 -fflags +bitexact Composite.flac

IMPORTANT:
If you change Composite.flac (or Composite.wav), also update:
web_tests/webaudio/resources/hrtf

Notes on ffmpeg command:
 * -compression_level 12: Enables the highest compression level
 * -exact_rice_parameters 1 : Forces encoder to calculate Rice parameters
   exactly rather than estimating them, which improves compression at the cost
   of a tiny bit of encoding time.
 * -lpc_type cholesky -lpc_passes 20: Uses the most thorough Linear Predictive
   Coding (LPC) algorithm (Cholesky factorization) and optimizes it over 20
   passes.
   * Note: Tested up to 30 passes, but 20 proved to be the sweet spot for this
     specific file; 30 passes actually increased the file size slightly due to
     coefficient overhead).
 * -map_metadata -1 -fflags +bitexact: Strips unnecessary container metadata
   and encoder version tags, saving extra bytes.
 * Also tested -multi_dim_quant, but it was extremely slow (taking hours for a
   1.3s clip) and not practical for the negligible gains it might offer.
